{{Redirect|Businessman}} {{Capitalism}} {{wikt | businessperson}}
A '''businessperson''' (also '''businessman''' or '''businesswoman''') is a person involved in the [[business sector]] – in particular someone undertaking activities ([[commerce|commercial]] or [[industry|industrial]]) for the purpose of generating [[cash flow]], [[sales]], and [[revenue]] utilizing a combination of [[Human capital|human]], [[Financial capital|financial]], [[intellectual capital|intellectual]] and [[physical capital]] with a view to fuelling [[economic development]] and [[Economic growth|growth]].<ref> Compare: {{cite web |url= http://www.businessdictionary.com/definition/businessman.html |title= businessman |year= 2018 |publisher= WebFinance Inc. |access-date= 2018-07-06 |quote= businessman[:] A person who is employed by an organization or company. Businessmen are often associated with white collar jobs. In order to avoid sexism or the perpetuation of stereotypes, the term is often replaced with "businessperson". The term "businesswoman" is less commonly used. }} </ref> An [[entrepreneur]] is an example of a businessperson.
The term "businessperson" may refer to a founder, owner, or majority shareholder of a [[commercial enterprise]]; or it can characterize a high-level [[senior management|executive]] who does the everyday running and management of a [[company]] even if that executive is not the owner.<ref> Compare: {{cite web | url= http://www.audioenglish.org/dictionary/businessman.htm | title = BUSINESSMAN | publisher = Audioenglish | accessdate = 2016-08-27 | quote = The noun BUSINESSMAN has 1 sense: 1. a person engaged in commercial or industrial business (especially an owner or executive) }} </ref> The term may sometimes refer to someone who is involved in an upper-level [[management]] role in a [[corporation]], company, enterprise, firm, [[organization]], or agency.{{cn|date=July 2018}}
==History== ===Prehistoric period: Traders=== Since a "businessman" can mean anyone in industry or commerce,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.audioenglish.org/dictionary/businessman.htm | title=BUSINESSMAN | publisher=Audioenglish | accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> businessmen have existed as long as industry and commerce have existed. "Commerce" can simply mean "[[trade]]", and trade has existed through all of [[recorded history]]. The first businessmen in human history were traders or [[merchants]].
===Medieval period: Rise of the merchant class=== Merchants emerged as a "[[class (social)|class]]" in [[medieval Italy]]. Between 1300 and 1500, modern [[accounting]], the [[bill of exchange]], and [[limited liability]] were invented, and thus the world saw "the first true bankers", who are certainly businessmen.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=J.M.|title=The Penguin History of the World, Sixth Edition|year=2013|publisher=Penguin|location=New York|pages=506}}</ref>
Around the same time, Europe saw the "emergence of rich merchants."<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=J.M.|title=The Penguin History of the World, Sixth Edition|year=2013|publisher=Penguin|location=New York|pages=509}}</ref> This "rise of the merchant class" came as Europe "needed a middleman" for the first time, and these "burghers" or "[[bourgeois]]" were the people who played this role.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=J.M.|title=The Penguin History of the World, Sixth Edition|year=2013|publisher=Penguin|location=New York|pages=510}}</ref>
===Renaissance to Enlightenment: Rise of the capitalist=== Europe became the dominant global commercial power in the 16th century, and as Europeans developed new tools for business, new types of business people began to use those tools. In this period, Europe developed and used [[banknote|paper money]], [[cheque|cheques]], and [[joint-stock companies]] (and their shares of [[stock]]).<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=J.M.|title=The Penguin History of the World, Sixth Edition|year=2013|publisher=Penguin|location=New York|pages=558}}</ref> Developments in [[actuarial science]] led to [[insurance]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=J.M.|title=The Penguin History of the World, Sixth Edition|year=2013|publisher=Penguin|location=New York|pages=559}}</ref> Together, these new tools were used by a new kind of businessman, the [[capitalist]]. These people owned or financed businesses as [[bankers]], but they were not merchants of goods. These capitalists were a major force in the [[Industrial Revolution]]...
===Modern period: Rise of the manager=== The newest kind of businessperson is the [[manager]]. One of the first true managers was [[Robert Owen]] (1771–1858), an industrialist in Scotland.<ref>{{cite book|last=Drucker|first=Peter|title=Management, Revised Edition|year=2008|publisher=Collins Business|location=New York|pages=13}}</ref> He studied the "problems of [[productivity]] and [[motivation]]", and was followed by [[Frederick Winslow Taylor]], who was the first person who studied [[work (project management)|work]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Drucker|first=Peter|title=Management, Revised Edition|year=2008|publisher=Collins Business|location=New York|pages=14}}</ref> After [[World War I]], management became popular due to the example of [[Herbert Hoover]] and the [[Harvard Business School]], which offered [[MBA|degrees in business administration]] (management).<ref>{{cite book|last=Drucker|first=Peter|title=Management, Revised Edition|year=2008|publisher=Collins Business|location=New York|pages=15–16}}</ref>
==Salary== Salaries for businesspeople vary.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bls.gov/ooh/business-and-financial/home.htm |title=Business and Financial Occupations |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Bureau of Labor and Statistics |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor|access-date=2015-09-18 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bls.gov/ooh/management/ |title=Management Occupations |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Bureau of Labor and Statistics |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor|access-date=2015-09-18 |quote=}}</ref> The salaries of the top CEOs can be millions of dollars per year. For example, Discovery Communications' head, [[David Zaslav|David M. Zaslav]], made $156 million in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aflcio.org/Corporate-Watch/Paywatch-2014/100-Highest-Paid-CEOs |title=100 Highest Paid CEOs |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=AFL-CIO |publisher= AFL-CIO |access-date=2015-09-18 |quote=}}</ref> The high salary which executives earn has often been a source of criticism with many believing that they are paid excessively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hbr.org/2014/09/ceos-get-paid-too-much-according-to-pretty-much-everyone-in-the-world/ |title=CEOs Get Paid Too Much |author=Gretchen Gavett |website=Harvard Business Review |publisher=Harvard Business Review |access-date=2015-09-18 |quote=}}</ref>
==Business guru== Some leading business theorists look to leaders in academic research on business or to successful business leaders for guidance. Collectively, these people are called "[[business guru]]s."
