{{Infobox NRHP | name = Davis Memorial Presbyterian Church | nrhp_type = | image = Davis Memorial Presbyterian Church.jpg | caption = The church from Randolph Avenue in 2014 | location= 450 Randolph Ave., [[Elkins, West Virginia]] | coordinates = {{coord|38|55|38.2|N|79|50|52.4|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = West Virginia#USA | built = 1894 | architect = Cassell, Charles E.; Harding, Clarence L. | architecture = Gothic Revival | added = April 20, 1984 | area = {{convert|0.3|acre}} | governing_body = Private | refnum = 84003664<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> }}
'''Davis Memorial Presbyterian Church''' is a historic [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]] [[Church (building)|church]] at 450 [[U.S. Route 250|Randolph Avenue]] in [[Elkins, West Virginia|Elkins]], [[Randolph County, West Virginia|Randolph County]], [[West Virginia]], [[United States]]. It was originally built in 1894 and 1895 after designs prepared by the Baltimore architect [[Charles E. Cassell]]. In 1921, an [[Akron plan]] Sunday School building was added to the north by [[Clarence L. Harding]] of Washington D. C. The building consists of a nave, an engaged tower, and a gable roofed structure located perpendicular to the nave. It is built of a granular conglomerate stone consisting of large, transparent quartz crystals bound in clay or silica. The style is [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic]], with Romanesque and eclectic influences.<ref name="dhr">{{cite web|url=http://www.wvculture.org/shpo/nr/pdf/randolph/84003664.pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination Form: Davis Memorial Presbyterian Church|date=November 1983|accessdate=2011-09-01 |author=James Patrick|publisher=State of West Virginia, West Virginia Division of Culture and History, Historic Preservation}}</ref>
It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1984.<ref name="nris"/>
